  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "### What these timings show\n\n- At small pole order (S1=S2=8) all three evaluation strategies are within noise of each other (~0.01–0.03s) — this is why the closed-form approach didn't feel faster in early testing.\n- Pushing S1=S2 up to 400 (the regime we'll actually need) separates them clearly: direct `Residue` grows roughly quadratically (5.3s at k=400), the closed-form Laguerre sum (`res1`/`res0`) stays close to linear (0.25s), and the \"clever\" truncated-power-series idea (`fastResidue`) turns out **not** to be an improvement — it's still roughly quadratic, because multiplying two truncated series whose coefficients are themselves polynomials in `w` costs about the same as differentiating directly. It's kept here as a documented dead end, not a recommendation.\n- The single biggest lever is whether `w` needs to stay symbolic. Plugging a numeric `w` directly into `LaguerreL` before summing (`closed400numDirect`) is ~80x faster than building the symbolic-in-`w` sum and substituting afterward, and ~1300x faster than symbolic `Residue`. If a specific numeric `w` is all that's needed downstream, evaluate numerically from the start.\n- Bottom line, carried over to `Clean/FastQ.wb`: use `res1`/`res0` (closed-form Laguerre), not direct `Residue` or the truncated-series approach, and substitute numeric `w` as early as possible when symbolic generality isn't required.",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "## Generalized wrapper: sum residues over an arbitrary polynomial's coefficients\n\n`doRes0`/`doRes1` generalize the `poly20`-specific sums above to any polynomial `f` in `u`. Promoted as-is to `Clean/FastQ.wb`.",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {
    "toolId": "X31sZmlsZQ%3D%3D"
   }
  },
  {
   "kind": 2,
   "value": "\ndoRes0[S1_,S2_,f_]:=Module[{nmax,coeffs,res},\n  nmax=Exponent[f,u];\n  coeffs=CoefficientList[f,u];\n  res=Plus@@(coeffs Table[res0[n,S1,S2],{n,0,nmax}]);\n  res\n  ]\n\ndoRes1[S1_,S2_,f_]:=Module[{nmax,coeffs,res},\n  nmax=Exponent[f,u];\n  coeffs=CoefficientList[f,u];\n  res=Plus@@(coeffs Table[res1[n,S1,S2],{n,0,nmax}]);\n  res\n  ]",
   "languageId": "wolfram",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "### Next steps\n\nNeed a Baxter equation and solver for the `[S1,S1,0,0] x [S2,S2,0,0]` representation.",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {}
  }
 ],
 "metadata": {}
